 To simplify the given equation, we can find a common denominator on the left-hand side. Structuring the denominator with the newfound common factor, we manipulate the expression in terms of $x$. We obtain: \begin{align*}
\frac A{x-1} &= \frac{A(x+1)}{(x-1)(x+1)} \\
\frac B{x+1} &= \frac{B(x-1)}{(x-1)(x+1)} \\
\frac{x+2}{x^2-1} &= \frac{x+2}{(x-1)(x+1)}.
\end{align*}
We can multiply every term by the common denominator to obtain: \begin{align*}
A(x+1) + B(x-1) &= (x+2)(x-1) \\
Ax + A + Bx - B &= x^2 - 1.
\end{align*}
Combining like terms, we group the parentheses and rewrite: \begin{align*}
(A+B)x + (A-B) &= x^2 - 1 \\
1 + (A-B) &= x^2 - 1 \\
A-B &= -2.
\end{align*}Therefore, $A - B = \boxed{-2}$.
